va, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bellais","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English (Northamptonshire):","(of Norman origin): apparently from Old French <i>bélier</i> ‘ram’, hence a nickname for someone thought to resemble a ram in some way or possibly a metonymic occupational name for a shepherd. In Northamptonshire the name attracts excrescent <i>-s</i> already by 1377."],"variants":[{"name":"Beller","meanings":["English: occupational name for a bell founder or bell ringer, from Middle English <i>beller</i>, an agent derivative of Old English <i>belle</i> ‘bell’. Compare   Bell   2.","German: habitational name for someone from any of several places called Bell in North Rhine-Westphalia or Bellen near Bremen.","German: nickname for a quarreller, from Middle High German <i>bellen</i> ‘to bicker, quarrel’."]},{"name":"Bellairs","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Bellars  , suggesting French <i>belle(s) aire(s)</i> ‘lovely demeanor’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Bellais was born in 1130, in England as the son of William De Bella Aqua. He had at least 1 son with Beatrix Southwell de Bellais. He died in 1155, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1130–1155":"1130–1155","1133–1155":"1133–1155","1150–1180":"1150–1180","–Male":"Surnud","1155":"1155","1133":"1133","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1130–1155":"1130–1155","1133–1155":"1133–1155","1150–1180":"1150–1180","–Male":"Kuollut","1155":"1155","1133":"1133","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1130–1155":"1130–1155","1133–1155":"1133–1155","1150–1180":"1150–1180","–Male":"Décédé","1155":"1155","1133":"1133","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert de Bellais est né en 1130, à Angleterre, fils de William De Bella Aqua. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Beatrix Southwell de Bellais. Il est décédé en 1155, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 25 ans."},"de":{"1130–1155":"1130–1155","1133–1155":"1133–1155","1150–1180":"1150–1180","–Male":"Verstorben","1155":"1155","1133":"1133","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","England":"England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Robert de Bellais wurde 1130 in England, als Sohn von William De Bella Aqua geboren. Er hatte mit Beatrix Southwell de Bellais mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb 1155 im Alter von 25 Jahren in England